title: For Sale:  18" Rainier Arms Barrel Custom Precision AR - Priced to Sell
postcontent:
I have a custom built AR-15 rifle chambered in .223 Wylde (will accept 5.56 ammunition. .223 Wylde is not the same as commercial .223) for sale/trade.

- 18" Rainier Arms Stainless Match Barrel
- 15" Midwest Industries Gen 2 SS FF Rail
- Nickel Boron BCG (PSA)
- Magpul Furniture
- Nikon 4-12x40 MILDOT Scope
- Upper and Lower are PSA
- 1x 20rd Gen 3 PMAG
- 19x Rounds of Hornady BTHP Match loaded ammo (I had twenty but f***ed up one of the rounds projectile tip while chambering it in another weapon).

Fired a total of 92 rounds through the rifle (55gr loaded to .223 specs / brass cased Tula under the "Perfetca" brand). Rifle functioned flawlessly during the course. Weather was clear, mid 50's and very strong fishtail winds with gusts of 20mph.

Best grouping was at 100m being at just over 3/4 inch (4 rounds center to center measure).

Worst grouping of the day was at 412 meters (laser ranged it) with 5 rounds in a 4.5" grouping. Being that this was 55gr Commercial .223 and Tula ammo on top of that (equates to roughly a 2-3 MOA round) and the extremely variable wind we had, I am very pleased with the performance of the rifle and can be confident saying that if match or simply higher quality loads were fired through it, the barrel would consistently hold sub MOA.

Sale of rifle does not include the monopod or suppressor in the picture. Sale does include a standard bipod not pictured.

title: For Sale:  FNH Husqvarna Browning 1907 in .380
postcontent:
If you are thinking that this looks like a Colt 1903 longslide (which was never made) you are right! Sort of... What we have here is a Fabrique Nationale d'Herstal Browning 1903 pattern modified to the specifications of the Swedish military for adoption in 1907 as their primary service pistol as the M1907. These guns were made by FN and imported to Sweden until the FN factory was captured by Germans during the Great War. After that Husqvarna began production and eventually produced them for Columbia and other countries after the end of WW1.

This great little gun served with distinction up until the adoption of the Lahti in the 1940's. Once out of field use, they were still preferred by police and officers due to their compact dimensions and great handling. They were also used by several European, Middle Eastern and South American countries as well as the Russian and Ottoman Empires! If you like unusual guns with a storied history, this one is for you.

This gun is in great shape considering its age. Finish is very good at around 92-95%, bore is good and still shoots great. These are hugely overbuilt by todays standards for .380 so I would have no worries shooting +p or defensive ammo out of it. Best of all, you are probably the only person at the range with one! Needless to say these don't pop up every day so don't let this one pass you by.

F2F within about an hour of Charlottesville. No lowballers or tire kickers please. Take a look at my other listings for more fun toys.

title: For Sale:  Vintage 1916 Colt 1911 4th year production
postcontent: For Sale I have a Vintage Colt 1911 manufactured in 1916. This pistol has a beautiful commercial frame that retains a conservative 85% of its beautiful Early Colt high polish bluing and is one of the nicest I've ever seen in my years of collecting 1911s. The Slide is a US Army Slide that is from the same timeframe as it has the Gothic lettering and rear prancing horse which was used in 1916 on the Army Models. My personal belief is this Firearm was bought as a private sidearm before WW1 then either brought to war by the person who bought it or shipped over by their family and while in service had a US Army slide put on it as the slide and frame match pretty well and seem to have been together for quite sometime. The slide does have more wear than the frame most likely from pulling it in and out of a holster with the most significant wear concentrated between the ejection port and the front sight. The slide is a mix of the Colt "Fine Finish" Bluing and a pleasant brown patina. This Old Colt is a great shooter and retains all of its original early pre WW1 parts including the milled cut thumb safety, milled cut slide stop, and double diamond wood grips. The barrel is a pre WW2 Springfield replacement with an excellent bore. Overall this is an excellent example of a vintage Colt. If someone could find a Commercial model slide to match the frame you would be looking at an extremely valuable $3000 plus 85-90% original Pre WW1 Colt 1911. Slides shouldn't be that hard to procure as they made the exact same Commercial slides from 1913-1920 with no changes. I will ship this firearm anywhere in the US with a copy of a valid FFL or C&R license. If this pistol isn't sold by this weekend it's going to be parted out and sold on gunbroker which would be a shame because this gun is a damn fine shooter. E-mail, call, or text REDACTED. Would consider partial trades for a small carry gun. Trade value must not be higher than $350 as I need at lease $1000 cash unless it's a really nice piece.

title: For Trade:  Finnish 91/30 and Romarms .380  (2 gun package)

The soviet stocks were thrown away and newer higher quality wood was put on.  The front sights were switched to blade sights and the gun was issued to finnish troops or put up in the armory.  These 91/30s are NOT as easy to find as the soviet 91/30s, they are rare and magnificent shooting, hunting, and show guns.  This gun is EXTREMELY accurate.  The next gun is my Walther clone, the Romarms .380  this was issued to the Romanian military and police until they recently went to glocks.  Its accuracy and power is phenomenal.  This gun does favor a right handed shooter,  it has a raised platform on the left grip for the shooter to rest his thumb.  This raises the stability and control on the gun.  I can throw in around 40 rounds for the .380  I would like to trade them as a package but the only gun i would trade by itself would be the .380  Both guns are in great condition. Im not interested in selling just trading, i can send pics upon request.  The finnish 91/30 is going for $350 average and the Romarms is about $250, with the ammo i can throw in for the 91/30 i can make the trade value an easy $700.
